         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ [J. Chester Jervis, Esq., of the Grampians, Victoria, sent a dried specimen of a beautiful star-flowered low myrtle shrub indigenous to that region. [...] The specimen was brought over by Mr. R. Ba...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">55.00.00</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To J. Chester Jervis</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. For the text given here, see the report of the meeting of the Royal Society of Tasmania, 7 January 1857, in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Courier </seg>(Hobart), 13 January 1857, p. 2.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[J. Chester Jervis, Esq., of the Grampians, Victoria, sent a dried specimen of a beautiful star-flowered low myrtle shrub indigenous to that region. [...] The specimen was brought over by Mr. R. Ballantyne, together with a letter touching the shrub from Dr. F. Mueller to Mr. Jervis, which was read.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M’s letter could not have been written later than 12 August 1855, when M left Moreton Bay (Brisbane) with the North Australian Exploring Expedition, since he had been out of contact with the settled parts of Australia since then; and it was almost certainly written before he left Melbourne in late June 1855 to join the expedition in Sydney.</p>
               </note> Dr. Mueller has named it <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Scariomyrtus%20hexamera">Scariomyrtus hexamera</name>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In a report on his tour of the Grampians (M to J. Foster. 15 January 1854), M noted the discovery of ‘an extremly beautiful and yet undescribed bush of Myrtaceae (to be named <name key="Scariomyrtus%20hexamera">Scariomyrtus hexamera</name>), forming a most singular genus in the series of this order’. The taxon was mentioned with a very brief description, as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Scaryomyrtus</seg>, in B54.06.01, p. 157.</p>
               </note>]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Scariomyrtus%20hexamera">Scariomyrtus hexamera</name>
            </p>
         </div>
